<h1>Saudi Arabia Visa Guide 2026</h1>
<p>Saudi Arabia's immigration system has undergone more change in the past five years than in the previous five decades combined. Vision 2030, the kingdom's sweeping economic diversification program, has demanded a corresponding overhaul of how the country attracts, manages, and retains international talent. The result is a visa system that is increasingly digital, more flexible than the traditional kafala model it partially replaces, and designed to accommodate everyone from entry-level construction workers to high-net-worth investors seeking permanent settlement. For the professional evaluating a Saudi career opportunity in 2026, understanding these changes is essential because the visa category you hold directly determines your rights, your mobility between employers, your ability to bring family, and your long-term options in the kingdom.</p>

<p>The digital transformation of Saudi immigration services has been one of the most visible aspects of this change. The Qiwa platform, operated by the Ministry of Human Resources and Social Development, handles all employment-related services including work permit issuance, contract registration, professional classification, and labor mobility transfers. The Absher platform, managed by the Ministry of Interior, serves as the resident-facing portal for visa renewals, exit and re-entry permits, dependent sponsorship applications, traffic fines, and civil affairs. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs oversees document attestation through its own electronic portal. Together, these three platforms have replaced most in-person visits to government offices with digital transactions that can be completed from a phone or computer, reducing processing times and eliminating many of the bureaucratic friction points that once characterized Saudi immigration.</p>

